  "summary": "Piston Issue",
  "environment_raw": null,
  "description": "By cloning a flying flying machine some parts of it disappear and get replaced to areas, where you can walk through but can t place anything. You also can t mine in this area. n n",
  "Steps to Reproduce": "1. Create a new Creative world with default settings.\n2. Build a simple flying machine using 2 sticky pistons, 2 slime blocks, and 1 observer.\n3. Activate the flying machine to ensure it operates correctly.\n4. Once the machine is flying, use the command '/clone' to clone the flying machine.\n5. Position the clone command to overlap with the original flying machine's area.\n6. Observe the cloned flying machine as it activates and moves.\n7. Check the area where the original flying machine was located for any missing parts.\n8. Walk through the area where the parts disappeared and note that you cannot place blocks or mine any blocks in that space.",
  "Environment": "Minecraft Java Edition Version 1.21.8",
  "Observed Behavior": "When a player clones a flying machine in Minecraft, certain components of the machine may fail to replicate correctly, resulting in their disappearance. Specifically, parts of the flying machine, such as pistons or slime blocks, may not appear in the cloned structure. Instead, these missing components can be replaced by invisible blocks or areas that players can walk through but cannot interact with. \n\nIn these affected areas, players are unable to place any blocks or mine existing blocks, effectively rendering the space non-functional. This issue creates \"ghost blocks\" that disrupt gameplay, as players may find themselves unable to build or alter the environment as intended. The presence of these unmineable areas can hinder the construction of additional structures or mechanisms, particularly in creative builds where the functionality of flying machines is often relied upon.\n\nThis behavior appears to be consistent across different instances of cloning flying machines, indicating a potential bug in the replication process that affects the integrity of the flying machine\u2019s components and the surrounding blocks.",
  "Expected Behavior": "When cloning a flying machine in Minecraft, all components of the machine should be duplicated accurately without any parts disappearing. The cloned flying machine should function identically to the original, allowing players to interact with all blocks within the machine's structure as intended. Players should be able to place and mine blocks in the area where the machine is cloned, and no invisible barriers should prevent interaction with the environment. The game should maintain consistent behavior in handling flying machines, following the established mechanics for block movement and interaction as outlined in the official Minecraft documentation.",
